##Switch is about to run out of products globally, and decentralizing the supply chain is imminent

“

Switch and its games are likely to see varying levels of price appreciation until the situation improves.

”

While the high price of "fitness ring adventure" has caused some consumer dissatisfaction, but it may soon even buy out.

According to Bloomberg, a source familiar with Nintendo's supply chain said production disruptions at the supply chain factories affected by the COVID-19 outbreak may have pushed the Switch into a global shortage, the US and European markets could be out of stock as early as April.

Production at Nintendo's Assembly plant in Vietnam, which makes consoles for Nintendo's US market, is being affected by parts suppliers in China, the person said. The shortage of parts in February and March will have a direct impact on Switch's April shipments, as existing inventory is already sold out in response to current order demand.

A Switch spokesperson has said that Chinese hardware and accessories supplies to Japan will be affected by work stoppages due to the outbreak, and that Japan is already largely out of Switch's retail inventory, but that the largest North American market will not be affected for the time being.

"We do not see any significant impact on shipments to the United States at this time, but we will remain vigilant and take appropriate action if necessary, " the spokesman said, "If the epidemic spreads more widely and lasts longer, the supply could be affected. "

That is more in line with the Bloomberg report. It is reported that the volume of Swtich arriving in the United States in February and March will not be affected as the goods have already left the country. The problem is that the cargo ships destined for the United States and European markets may be affected in April and beyond, inadequate access to Switch in both regions.

North America, which accounts for 43 per cent of Nintendo's core business, is its biggest market and could have a big impact on the company's performance in fiscal 2020 if there is a long-term shortage in the region.

A number of companies in a similar position, such as Nintendo, are likely to respond by decentralising their supply chains.

"The impact on production has started to become apparent, " Nintendo's president, Toshitaro Furukawa, said at a earnings news conference in January in response to the new pneumonia. Discussions have begun to expand production sites in view of the multiple risks.

Lu Jiaao, a semiconductor industry analyst for UBS Asia Pacific, told interface news that decentralisation of supply chains was already happening globally and had not been obvious before, but that the epidemic was forcing supply chains to take action.

Until that happens, the price of Switch and its games is likely to rise in varying degrees.

"Don't buy money management buy RingFit, " says one consumer, who has to lament the prices of gyms these days. Interface news reporters found that now Taobao, jd.com, leisure fish and other e-commerce trading platform search "fitness ring" , the price is generally around 1800 yuan to 2000 yuan.

When it first went on sale, the American version of the exercise ring adventure cost $79.99, and the Japanese version cost 7,980 yen, both around 500 yuan, meaning the price has tripled or quadrupled.

In fact, the popular Swtich game, which was released in October 2019, had risen in price well before the epidemic hit, and the spot price in China was more than 800 yuan and close to 900 yuan a month later.

Nintendo is growing at a decent pace. Net sales for the latest fiscal year were 1,022.6 billion yen, up 2.5 percent from 997.3 billion yen in the previous fiscal year, and operating income was 262.9 billion yen, up 19.5 percent from 220 billion yen in the previous fiscal year, according to its Jan. 30 report.

More than 52.48 million Switch consoles and 310 million software games have been sold worldwide.

That said, for Nintendo, it's important to keep the outbreak to a minimum, otherwise sales and revenue will suffer for nearly a year.
